        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimated the CO fluxes of our sources from their SFR and redshift following Sargent et al. (2013). We assume a line width of 400km/s and compute the sensitivity in the same bandwidth. We found similar integrated fluxes of ~3 mJy for our four galaxies. We have however to take into account that this flux will be split between several beam.  The typical extension of our galaxies is 1” and we chose the highest possible resolution of ~0.5” which can be reached for all the sources in cycle 2(0.476” for PACSMS28 observed at 86 GHz).  We thus request a 0.15 mJy/beam sensitivity to get a 5 sigma detection in 4 beam elements. 2 sources can be observed with the same tuning, reducing slightly the overheads.  This is not the case for the two other sources.

We checked that this strategy is reasonable producing a simulated image of our sources assuming that the CO distribution will follow the I-band flux (see Fig. 2). The disk and some isolated clumps are well detected on this image. We can expect that the bulge will be fainter in real data. The disk could thus be brighter and the source may look more extended in the real ALMA data. As instance, in PACS02MS, 03 and 28, the disk in only marginally detected on the simulation and the bulge is booming. This could be the contrary in the real data. Finally, we could expect from theoretical predictions that one or two clumps concentrate a major fraction of the gas. If this is correct, they should be detected in the ALMA data (e.g. we already see some characteristic patterns in PACSMS28). If these clumps are more numerous, there could be an effect of confusion, but the clumpiness could be characterized through the fluctuations of density across the disk. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
