        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimated the flux of the continuum in band 3 using Magids et al. (2012) MS templates and found that the continuum signal in a 7.5 Ghz bandwidth at the chosen depth of our observations will be only ~1sigma/beam for our four sources. We thus request an additional band-6 observation to get the continuum with sensitivity and resolution similar to the CO in band 3. We use a single tuning for all sources to minimize the calibration overheads. The expected total integrated flux of the faintest object is 1.3 mJy. We thus need a sensitivity of 0.065 mJy/beam to match the criterion of 5sigma in 4 beams used for CO in band 3.

We tune the setting of the band in order to cover the range 256.9 and 259.036 GHz where some bright line are expected (CO76 and CI 3P2-1 for PACSMS02 and PACSMS10, CO65 for PACSMS28).  This range is covered by the lower side band to have the upper side band at the highest possible frequency, where the dust continuum is the brightest. The flux density (in mJy) of these lines is expected close from the one of CO2-1 or CO3-2 (e.g.  Alaghband-Zadeh et al. 2013, Aravena et al. 2013, Spikler et al. in prep.) and should thus be easily detected, especially if we consider that the sensitivity in band 6 will be 1.5 times better than in band 3. This will help to improve the precision of the dynamical modeling.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
